Multivariate analyses of community structure (classical)

2019-01-18

This notebook contains all (classical) multivariate analyses of zoobenthic community structure: MDS, envfit, ANOSIM & SIMPER and friends.
All my notebooks are intended to be as self-contained as possible, so there will be a relatively repetitive setup/data import/preparation part.

Envfit - sand stations.

Envfit can be used to determine which environmental parameters correlate best with the ordination (and thus explain best the observed dissimilarities in the zoobenthic community structure between stations).
As per the PCA results, from the water column parameters, I’ll use the most significant ones (best correlated with PCA axes): LUSI, secchi, seston, PO4, NH4, NO3 + all sediment parameters (except the most inter-correlated): TOM, moisture content, gravel and silt_clay.
First, import the environmental parameters (from the cleaned files).
For the water column, I’ll use the long-term means wherever possible (and repeat each value 9 times per station to match the number of zoobenthic replicates that I have).

water.sand.all <- read_csv(here(save.dir, "water_column_summary_LT.csv"))

(water.sand <- water.sand.all %>% 
    ## filter only the sand stations
    filter(station %in% c("Kraimorie", "Chukalya", "Akin", "Sozopol", "Agalina", "Paraskeva")) %>%

    select(station, NH4_mean, NO3_mean, PO4_mean, seston_mean, secchi_mean) %>%

The observed MDS grouping is described 1) by the eutrophication/anthropogenic pressure gradient (water column parameters + LUSI), but also 2) by the sediment parameters - grain size & organic matter. That’s why S5-Agalina is separate from the others - it has coarser sediments (more gravel) + organic matter because it’s close to a natural reef, but it’s in the outer bay - so less nutrients and more transparent water. That’s why its community structure is also very distinct.
This grouping should be confirmed through ANOSIM, and if deemed valid - SIMPER to see which the distinctive species are.

ANOSIM - sand stations.

This is a non-parametric permutation procedure applied to the rank (similarity) matrix underlying the ordination or classification of the samples.
R statistic: -1 to 1; 1 = all replicates within sites are more similar to each other than to any other replicate from a different site; 0 = H0 is true (the same average similarities between and within sites). Usually 0 < R < 1 => some degree of difference observed between sites.
Best course of analysis: 1) global ANOSIM - overall difference between groups; if significant - 2) where does the main between-group difference come from?
=> examine R values for each pairwise comparison: large = complete separation, small - little or no difference.
NB ANOSIM doesn’t really have much statistical power and tends to get confounded by higher variances!..

Let’s try grouping by the apparent MDS clusters.

Now, the within-group SIMPER (which species are the most characteristic of each group) - custom function, because vegan doesn’t provide this option, with good reason..

attr(,"overall.group.similarity")
       3        4        2        1 
60.01474 63.01196 48.74388 66.55417

So most group similarities are around 60%. Group 1 (S4-S6) has the lowest - 48.7%. It’s not very surprising; if you look at the MDS, these samples are more dispersed - there is some variation in community composition, but I’m still inclined to consider it a single group because of the sediment composition, the depth and the community dominants.
According to the Bulgarian national classification, the stations fall into the following biotopes:
* group 1 (S4-S6): “Infralittoral fine and medium sand dominated by Chamelea gallina, Lentidium mediterraneum and Tellina tenuis” (ILitFSCham). Only C. gallina is singled out by the within-group SIMPER, thanks to its dominance in the samples.. The other species are really minor, seen in only a few of the samples and only as a few individuals. So, SIMPER really does focus on species with large variance, and not necessarily on characterstic ones.
* group 2 (S5): “Infralittoral mixed sediments with diverse fauna” (ILitMSVar) - also one of the national subtypes, from the latest report, but without ecological state limits - with many species having significant and really close contributions to the community composition. The dominants are Microdeutopus versiculatus, Protodorvillea kefersteini, Melita palmata, Eurydice dollfusi, etc. It really is pretty unique in composition - the closest would be S3, but the sediment composition distingishes it enough..
* group 3 (S1-S2): “Infralittoral sandy muds dominated by Melinna palmata, Anadara kagoshimensis, Heteromastus filiformis” (ILitMMelin). It’s not one of the national biotopes, either. Dominants according to SIMPER: H. filiformis, Oligochaeta, M. palmata, Prionospio cirrifera, A. kagoshimensis. * group 4 (S3): this corresponds most closely to the subtype “Infralittoral medium and coarse sands dominated by Upogebia pusilla” (ILitCSUpog) (even though U.pusilla itself is absent from the samples). Dominants: Protodorvillea kefersteini, Oligochaeta, Branchiostoma lanceolatum, Ophelia limacina, Chamelea gallina.

PERMANOVA - environmental parameters, sand stations

This is multivariate ANOVA based on dissimilarities (in package vegan - function adonis).
From the help file: used for partitioning distance matrices among sources of variation and fitting linear models (e.g., factors, polynomial regression) to distance matrices; uses a permutation test with pseudo-F ratios.

Make a distance matrix of the communities, and check multivariate homogeneity of groups dispersions (variances) - a PERMANOVA assumption.

bioenv - environmental parameters, sand stations

This is the last thing I’m going to try - bioenv (I think it’s equivalent to the PRIMER function of the same name).
It selects all possible subsets of environmental variables, finds the correlation between community dissimilarities and environmental distances, and for each size of subsets, saves the best result. The idea is to get the most parsimonious model that best explains the observed community differences.
I don’t expect this to actually perform better (same underlying environmental data, same problems with grossly oversimplified variables).

bioenv.sand

PERMANOVA - environmental parameters, seagrass stations

Same as for the sand stations.. Make a distance matrix of the communities, and check multivariate homogeneity of groups dispersions (variances) - a PERMANOVA assumption.

## make distance matrix of the seagrass communities (square root transformed)
dist.matrix.zostera <- vegdist(zoo.abnd.zostera %>% 
                                 select(-c(station:replicate)) %>%
                                 mutate_all(sqrt))

## check the dispersion between groups - using the clusters from the MDS
(betadisper.zostera <- betadisper(dist.matrix.zostera, 
                                  group = clusters.st.zostera)
)

anova(betadisper.zostera)

So again there are significant differences in dispersion between groups that might also contribute to any significant effect detected by PERMANOVA..

## construct equation for PERMANOVA. NB remove the secchi depth, because it has NaNs (for Vromos), which prevent the analysis from running - unequal matrices.. 
permanova.eq.zostera <- paste("dist.matrix.zostera", 
                              paste(names(env.data.ordi.zostera %>% select(-secchi)), collapse = "+"), 
                              sep = " ~ ")

## set blocks for the permutations
permutations.zostera <- how(nperm = 999)
setBlocks(permutations.zostera) <- clusters.st.zostera
 
## run the PERMANOVA with the parameters defined above  
(permanova.env.zostera <- adonis(as.formula(permanova.eq.zostera),
                                 data = env.data.ordi.zostera, 
                                 permutations = permutations.zostera)
)

All right, so the most significant parameters are again eutrophication/pollution parameters - LUSI, and sediment grain size (sand and silt), and also seagrass density (shoot count).

Save the PERMANOVA for the seagrass stations.

write_rds(permanova.env.zostera, 
          here(save.dir, "permanova_env_params_zostera.RDS"))
bioenv - environmental parameters, seagrass stations

So, for consistency, here is bioenv on the environmental parameters at the seagrass stations.
It selects all possible subsets of environmental variables, finds the correlation between community dissimilarities and environmental distances, and for each size of subsets, saves the best result. The idea is to get the most parsimonious model that best explains the observed community differences.
I don’t expect this to actually perform better (same underlying environmental data, same problems with grossly oversimplified variables).

## use the same equation and data as for the PERMANOVA above
bioenv.zostera <- bioenv(as.formula(permanova.eq.zostera), 
                         data = env.data.ordi.zostera, 
                         method = "spearman", 
                         metric = "euclidean")

bioenv.zostera
summary(bioenv.zostera)

Interestingly, here the bioenv procedure suggests that the sediment grain size (% sand) and the seagrass shoot density are the parameters that best explain the observed community differences. Could be - I wouldn’t say there are much differences at all, see the MDS..

write_rds(bioenv.zostera, 
          here(save.dir, "bioenv_zostera.RDS"))

Plot the MDS, colouring the points by site..

Adding in the 95% confidence interval to make the mess somewhat clearer, it kinda-sorta seems that site K MIGHT be considered a little different - but if you squint really really hard. Mostly, I don’t think the data allows to distinguish the sites; the differences in community structure are likely to be due to the habitats (with the sites contributing some secondary effects) - see the MDS plot coloured by habitat below.

Now this picture is interesting - the seagrass samples are found compactly in the middle, with the sand samples surrounding them.. If we check the goodness-of-fit plot, the seagrass samples are also better represented (-> smaller circles). The sand samples contain very few species and individuals, therefore they are more dispersed - hence the high differences.. I want to stress once again that the most likely reason for the poor species diversity, etc. is my own inexperience - I was still learning then, and it’s highly likely that I missed a lot.. Should have maybe kept the samples, then I could have come back to them - but again, due to inexperience I didn’t know..

All in all, it appears that in the preliminary experiment, the sand communities in Sozopol Bay are somewhat distinct from the seagrass ones, but not clearly so. One possible reason could be that the sand samples were not taken far enough from the seagrass to be “free” from its influence. Especially true in the case of site G (Gradina) - the unvegetated samples were taken from bare patches within the seagrass meadow itself (because the meadow is very large).

Make a combined MDS plot in ggplot - NOT using my nice custom function, because it doesn’t allow for easy mapping of two factors - to colours and shapes, for example.

When we examine (visually) the differences between habitats - not sure if this is a valid approach - it’s clear that any strong site differences are due to the sand samples. The seagrass samples form a much more compact group at the center. Again, I think this is caused by the particular shortcomings of the 2012 samples.

L.orbiculatus is a very characteristic seagrass-associated bivalve which has endosymbiotic sulfate-reducing bacteria contributing to sometimes ~60% of its nutrition - it therefore likes the reduced sediments in seagrass beds.

simper.wn.gr.2012.habitats <- simper_within_group(zoo.abnd.2012 %>% select(-c(site:replicate)),
                                                  group = zoo.abnd.2012 %>% pull(habitat))
simper.wn.gr.2012.habitats
$S

$Z

attr(,"overall.group.similarity")
       S        Z 
26.99125 49.32594

As I said before - sand samples have pretty low average group similarity, 27% (you can see that, they’re dispersed around the MDS plot). This is not due to striking differences between sites, but to the taxonomic identification problems causing high variability. The most characteristic species for the sand habitat are: B.reticulatum, L.orbiculatus, C.gallina, C.capitata. The most characteristic species for the seagrass habitat are: B.reticulatum, L.orbiculatus, M.lineatus, R.membranacea. See, they overlap; there is no clear difference sand/seagrass here..

SIMPER within sites..

simper.wn.gr.2012.sites <- simper_within_group(zoo.abnd.2012 %>% select(-c(site:replicate)),
                                               group = zoo.abnd.2012 %>% pull(site))
simper.wn.gr.2012.sites
$Konski

$Ribka

$Gradina

attr(,"overall.group.similarity")
  Konski    Ribka  Gradina 
45.00040 42.98813 37.28550

For the site groupings, Konski seems to have more Oligochaetes and Capitellid and spionid polychaetes - consistent with its proximity to the disturbance source - more organic loading so a higher proportion of tolerant species. Ribka and Gradina, on the other hand, have mostly mollusks - B.reticulatum, L.orbiculatus, R.membranacea.. The within-group similarities here are better than at the habitat level (because the sand samples are so very different among themselves).
